msDesc.head: Peter Lombard, Sententiarum libri quatuor with commentary by Hugh of St-Cher

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil; repeats no.s 143 and 224.

collation.catchwords: Catchwords on quires 3, 5 and 12. Pecia numbers (I-XIIII) on quire 2-20.

p.note: Top left corner, National Library book label with the current signum: A 150. Top of page, in black ink in a medieval hand: Liber Sententiarum Magistri petri lombardi.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Tan leather over bevelled wooden boards. 8 double raised bands and 2 endbands. Originally, 2 pin clasps with leather straps. , in black ink: 28; stamped in gold: A 150; on paper label, Jache's signum in brown ink: 25; on paper label, Hammarsköld's signum in brown ink: e.30.3. 12; remnants of paper label.
binding.condition: Leather worn with a few holes, wormholes, and tears around ; corners, top of , and section of repaired with brown leather patches. Clasps and straps missing; holes from 2 pins.

history.provenance: The manuscript bears the marks of several of its previous owners (see Additions). It is first mentioned at the National Library in Jache's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) and listed there as no. 25; before 1698, the manuscript, according to a former librarian, had the signum 192, which was listed on the now damaged paper label on the ; it is listed in Hammarsköld’s catalogue from the 19th century (U 133) as e.30.3.12. The signum 28, found on the , has not been identified.

note.p: Hugh's commentary was identified by Stegmüller (1948) as a first redaction, but has been shown by Principe (1963) to be an abridgement.

supportDesc.foliation: , contemporary foliation (ii-v) in Roman numerals in brown ink.
supportDesc.condition: Some stains, tears, and holes; numerous wormholes on first few folios. , parchment cut and sewn with blue thread.

layout.note: Lombard's text is written in two-column format with Hugh's commentary as a marginal and interlinear gloss. Ruling in lead. Some pages are ruled for Lombard's text only, e.g. , and some both for Lombard's text and Hugh's commentary, e.g. .

p.note: Bottom left corner, in pencil by a modern hand: 28.

Top right corner in brown ink by a medieval hand: Gillibertus habuit tres modios duobus sextariis minus Ego G duos modios et septem sextarios et summa tocius c solidi Vnde mihi debet l et vi solidos et iii obolos gillibertus et meum valet xl et iiii solidos iii obolis minus.
Lower mid page, in black ink by a medieval hand: hugo de xl solidos de Petro supra quasdem sentencias mutatos die martis post festum beati nicolai hyemalis.

Top of page, smudged and now almost entirely illegible, but according to a former librarian: Iste liber est domini Bernardi de Pomeriis, archid ... et accommodauit ... ator scol... de ... degentibis Parisiis. On top of line 2 of prior writing, in ink by a medieval hand, smudged and barely legible: Iste sentencie sunt fratri petri
.

The leaf is covered in notes on various theological questions and excerpts from authorities in several different hands. Mid page, in faded brown ink: Liber iste est conuentus de Kar
; and further down, in the same faded ink: Iste liber est conuentus de Kar
.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink; section rubrics in red ink.
decoDesc.decoNote: Opening puzzle initial O over 7 lines in red and blue ink with flourishing in red and blue in counterspace and, along margin, flourishing in blue extending from top to bottom of page. Puzzle initials over 7-8 lines in red and blue ink, with flourishing in red and/or blue in counterspace and, along margin, flourishing in red and/or blue extending from between 20 lines to the edge of the page (e.g. ); guide letters still visible in many places (e.g. ). Plain initials over 1-2 lines alternating in red and blue ink with flourishing alternating in red and blue.
